<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="922" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d922">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/643</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The German Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BCJHV1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bernstorff</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">German Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-11">
                                <hi rend="italic">November 11, 1914</hi>.</date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received November 12</hi>.] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Translation]</p>
                        <p rend="flushleft">J. No. A 2116]</p>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: I have the honor to
                            draw your excellency’s attention to the announcement made in No. 260 of
                            the <hi rend="italic">Daily Consular and Trade Reports</hi>, published
                            by the Department of Commerce, under No. 14333 of “Foreign Trade
                            Opportunities,” page 607, of the opportunity to deliver war material to
                            the English Government.<note n="1" xml:id="d922fn1">For the substance of
                                the item referred to, see the Secretary’s answer of January 15,
                                1915, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_579">p.
                                    579</ref>.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Since the offices of the Bureau of Foreign and Domestic Trade are, as I
                            have come to learn, at the disposal of the agents of foreign governments
                            to help the transaction of business between them and American
                            manufacturers, I beg your excellency kindly to let me know whether their
                            activities as go-betweens also include delivery of war material.</p>
                        <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BCJHV1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">J. Bernstorff</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>